body:
I found a mismatch between the waveforms and my RTL codes when I  using a generated clock inside a block triggered by the same clock.
After debuging, I build the following concise testcase that can repeat my case.

testcase:
```v
// demo.v
module top (
    input   wire    clk,
    input   wire    gate,
    output  reg     f2
);
wire    clk1;
reg     f0;
reg     f1;
assign clk1 = clk & (~gate);
always @ (posedge clk) begin
    f0 <= ~f0;
    f1 <= f0;
    $display("{f0, f1, f2} == {%d, %d, %d}", f0, f1, f2);
end
always @ (posedge clk1) begin
    if (clk1) begin
        f2 <= f1;
    end
end
endmodule
```
verilator arguments are `--cc`
And here is my c++ wrapper
```cpp
// sim_main.cpp
#include "Vdemo.h"
#include "verilated.h"

vluint64_t main_time = 0;
double sc_time_stamp() { return main_time; }

int main(int argc, char** argv, char** env) {
    Verilated::commandArgs(argc, argv);
    Vdemo* top = new Vdemo;
    top->gate = 0;
    while (!Verilated::gotFinish() && main_time < 40) {
        top->eval();
        main_time++;
        top->clk = !top->clk;
    }
    delete top;
    exit(0);
}
```
The output is clear to see the problem, where `f1` and `f2` flip simultaneously. But in my design, `f2` should delayed by `f1`
```
// screen output
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
{f0, f1, f2} == {0, 1, 1}
{f0, f1, f2} == {1, 0, 0}
```

In my real project, codes like this were widely exist  and more complicated, I hope Verilator can do better in this situation. If you can't get what I mean, please let me know, I will explain more.

Looking forward to your reply.
